<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - CYLINDER HEAD AND VALVES - CYLINDER HEAD RECONDITIONING - VALVE
        AND VALVE GUIDE RECONDITIONING
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="23">
        <title>VALVE AND VALVE GUIDE RECONDITIONING</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Remove Valves</title>
            <para>Using a valve spring compressor tool, remove the valves as follows:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the valve spring compressor over the valve to be removed and compress the
                    spring.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the valve spring locks (keepers). Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150433">4.33</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the valve spring compressor tool.</para>
                <figure id="ef4150431" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12040" filename="../figcg1/CG12040.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.31. Install Coolant Director.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150432" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12041" filename="../figcg1/CG12041.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.32. Recess Water Director.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150433" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12042" filename="../figcg1/CG12042.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.33. Remove Valve Spring Locks.</caption>
                </figure>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">For Engines Built After S/N 594857</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the valve rotator, valve spring, stem shield assembly and valve as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150434">4.34</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">For Engines Built Before S/N 594858</emph>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the valve rotator, valve spring, oil shield, and valve spring seat from the valve
                    guide, then remove the valve. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150435">4.35</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>If valve does not slide out easily, inspect the valve stem for burrs. If a burr is
                            present, remove it to prevent valve guide damage. Keep valves in order if they are to be
                            reinstalled into their original positions.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Clean Valve Guides</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With valves removed, clean all valve guides using a nylon brush, soap and water. Refer
                    to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150436">4.36</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="hl4150404">
            <title>Inspect Valve Guides</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position an inspection light at the bottom of the valve guide bores and visually examine
                    the walls for burning, cracking or loss of spiral grooves. Replace any guides which do not pass the
                    visual inspection.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The spiral grooves on the valve guides are for oil retention.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4150434" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14691" filename="../figcg1/CG14691.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.34. Remove Valve Rotator, Spring and Stem Seal Assembly.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150435" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14687" filename="../figcg1/CG14687.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.35. Remove the Valve Spring Seat and Valve.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150436" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14688" filename="../figcg1/CG14688.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.36. Clean Valve Guide Bores.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure each valve guide using a telescoping gauge and outside micrometer (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150437">4.37</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ). If guide exceeds specifications, replace guide.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>MEASURE VALVE GUIDES WITHIN 1/4 INCH OF EACH END OF THE GUIDE AND 90&#176; FROM THE
                            CRANKSHAFT CENTER-LINE. RECORD VALVE GUIDE I.D. READINGS SO VALVE-TO-GUIDE RUNNING CLEARANCE
                            MAY BE DETERMINED LATER.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Replace Valve Guides</title>
            <para>Remove any valve guides which do not pass the inspection criteria as follows:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert the valve guide remover
                    <emph type="bold">SE-1722</emph>
                    into the guide from the valve port side of the cylinder head.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drive out the valve guide with a hammer. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150438">4.38</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>
                            <emph type="underscr">DO NOT</emph>
                            USE NEW SHORTER VALVE GUIDE (P/N 1 815 264 C1) FOR SERVICE ON CYLINDER HEADS PRIOR TO S/N
                            594858. USING THE SHORTER GUIDE WILL CAUSE INTERFERENCE AND DAMAGE TO THE ENGINE. MEASURE
                            VALVE GUIDE TO VERIFY LENGTH.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new valve guide inserts as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Adjust the valve guide installer tool,
                        <emph type="bold">SE-1943</emph>, using a caliper (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150439">4.39</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>REFER TO
                                <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>
                                FOR CORRECT VALVE GUIDE HEIGHT (ABOVE TOP DECK OF THE CYLINDER HEAD) BEFORE INSTALLING
                                VALVE GUIDE. ADJUST THE TOOL TO CORRESPOND TO DESIRED VALVE GUIDE HEIGHT.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="ef4150437" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg14692" filename="../figcg1/CG14692.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.37. Measure Valve Guide I.D.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef4150438" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11377" filename="../figcg1/CG11377.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.38. Remove Valve Guide.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef4150439" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11378" filename="../figcg1/CG11378.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.39. Adjust Valve Guide Installer Tool to Specified Height.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lubricate the valve guide insert using clean engine oil and drive into the cylinder
                        head until the installer tool bottoms against the cylinder head. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150440">4.40</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>INSTALL THE VALVE GUIDE INSERTS WITH THE 45&#176; (EARLY PRODUCTION 30&#176;) CHAMFER
                                END UP AND THE INTERNAL SPIRAL THREADED PORTION DOWN. THE CHAMFER EDGE UP ALLOWS EXCESS
                                OIL TO DRAIN AWAY FROM THE STEM WHILE THE INTERNAL THREADS AT THE BOTTOM PROVIDE PROPER
                                OIL RETENTION.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Ream valve guide, after installation, using a 0.3740 in. reamer
                        <emph type="bold">SE-2215</emph>
                        (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150441">4.41</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Reaming is required to re-size the guide and to remove any peening resulting from the
                                guide installation process.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Clean valve guides as described in Figure
                                <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150441">4.41</hotlnk>.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Clean Valves</title>
            <para>Remove all carbon from the valve stems and valve heads.</para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Inspect Valves</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect each valve, replacing any that show evidence of burn marks, warpage,
                    scuffing or bending.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure each valve stem for wear using a micrometer to measure valve stem diameter.
                    Record the readings.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Current production and service exhaust valves are tapered in the stem area. Refer to
                            Figure
                            <hotlnk document="e415_44.xml" xrefid="ef4150407">4.7</hotlnk>
                            for dimensions of exhaust valves.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Measure valves at three locations 90&#176; apart. Refer to the "
                            <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>" and
                            replace valves which exceed the minimum stem diameter specification.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4150440" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14689" filename="../figcg1/CG14689.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.40. Install Valve Guide.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150441" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg14693" filename="../figcg1/CG14693.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.41. Ream Valve Guides.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the valve stem diameter and valve guide inside diameter measurements, recorded
                    earlier (see
                    <hotlnk xrefid="hl4150404">"INSPECT VALVE GUIDES"</hotlnk>
                    in this section), determine valve stem-to-guide running clearance. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>. Replace valve or
                    valve guide as required.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Reface Valves</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If valves are in serviceable condition, reface the valve to the specified angle, as required.
                        Refer to Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150442">4.42</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reface the valves as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Dress the cutting stone, prior to refacing the valves, using the dressing stud
                        attachment on the grinder.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the valve in the grinder and set to the specified angle.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Grind the valve face. Remove only the minimum amount of material necessary to true
                        up the valve face. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150443">4.43</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure valve face margin at four locations using a caliper. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150444">4.44</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The minimum valve face margin (See
                            <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>) must be
                            maintained across the entire valve face. An insufficient margin will
                            <emph type="underscr">NOT</emph>
                            provide proper heat dissipation and lead to valve warpage or breakage. Intake and exhaust
                            valve margins are different. Replace the valve if the margin is less than the specified
                            minimum, after grinding.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4150442" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11326" filename="../figcg1/CG11326.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.42. Valve Face Angles.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150443" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11069" filename="../figcg1/CG11069.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.43. Grind Valve Face Angle.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150444" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11068" filename="../figcg1/CG11068.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.44. Measure Valve Face Margin.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reface the valve stem tip as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Dress the cutting stone using the dressing stud on the grinder.</para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>WHEN RESURFACING VALVE STEM TIP, LEAVE SUFFICIENT MATERIAL SO THE ROCKER ARM DOES NOT
                                CONTACT THE VALVE SPRING LOCKS OR ROTATORS, DURING OPERATION.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the valve in the grinder as shown in
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150445">4.45</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Touch the valve stem tip to the cutting stone removing only a minimum of material.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Refacing the valve stem tip provides a new wear surface for the rocker arm.</para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After resurfacing valves, insert valves in clean valve guide and check valve face
                    contact with valve seat using Prussian Blue(r) (or equivalent) as follows:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Spread thin film of Prussian Blue(r) on valve face. Insert valve into its guide.
                        Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150446">4.46</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Apply pressure on exact center of valve head while making a quarter turn in the
                        seat. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150447">4.47</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove valve, inspect impression made on seat and on valve face.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Bluing should appear around entire contact surface of valve face and valve seat to
                        be acceptable.
                        <emph type="bold">CHECK SEVERAL TIMES TO PREVENT ERROR.</emph>
                        If acceptable, proceed with valve installation.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>IF SEATS ARE ACCEPTABLE, INSTALL THE VALVES WITHOUT GRINDING THE SEATS. IF VOIDS
                                APPEAR IN THE BLUING, SEAT GRINDING IS REQUIRED.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="ef4150445" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg12046" filename="../figcg1/CG12046.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.45. Reface Valve Stem Tip.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef4150446" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11382" filename="../figcg1/CG11382.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.46. Apply Bluing to Valve Face.</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef4150447" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11383" filename="../figcg1/CG11383.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.47. Check Valve Seat Contact.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="hl4150405">
            <title>Valve Seat Grinding</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If required, resurface the valve seat as follows: (Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150448">4.48</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lightly lubricate and install the correct size pilot into the valve guide.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Choose the correct angle grinding stone and dress the stone. Refer to
                        <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>
                        for valve seat angles.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the grinding stone over the pilot.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Lower grinder head over pilot shank until wheel barely clears the valve seat. Turn
                        on power. GENTLY apply grinding wheel to valve seat with little pressure other than weight of
                        the wheel.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Raise wheel frequently to prevent overheating.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Grind seat to a smooth even finish.</para>
                    <figure id="ef4150448" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11635" filename="../figcg1/CG11635.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4.48. Grind Valve Seat.</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After grinding, check valve seat width using a caliper as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150449">4.49</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>
                    for seat width limits. If seat widths are excessive, they may be corrected by grinding with a 15&#176;
                    smaller angle stone.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check valve recession using a straightedge and feeler gauge or a surface gauge. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figures
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150450">4.50</hotlnk>
                        and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150451">4.51</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>
                    for recession limits. If valve recession is excessive, install a new valve or replace the valve
                    seat. If the valve protrudes above the deck, regrind the valve seat.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>IF A NEW VALVE WILL NOT CORRECT AN EXCESSIVE RECESSION CONDITION, THE VALVE SEAT MUST BE
                            REPLACED AND REGROUND. IF THE VALVE FACE PROTRUDES ABOVE THE DECK, THE VALVE SEAT WILL HAVE
                            TO BE REGROUND DEEPER INTO THE HEAD. AFTER REGRINDING ANY SEAT, RECHECK THE SEAT WIDTH
                            (FIGURE
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150449">4.49</hotlnk>) AND CONFIRM VALVE SEAT CONTACT USING PRUSSIAN
                            BLUE(r) (FIGURES
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150446">4.46</hotlnk>
                            AND
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150447">4.47</hotlnk>) CLEAN VALVE GUIDES AS DESCRIBED IN FIGURE
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150436">4.36</hotlnk>.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4150449" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11381" filename="../figcg1/CG11381.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.49. Measure Valve Seat Width.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150450" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12049" filename="../figcg1/CG12049.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.50. Measure Valve Recession - Method One.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150451" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12050" filename="../figcg1/CG12050.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.51. Measure Valve Recession - Method Two.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After grinding the valve seat, check the seat for runout, using an appropriate dial
                    indicator. Valve seat runout should not exceed limits shown in
                    <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150401.xml" xrefid="hl4150401">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>IF VALVE SEAT RUNOUT, CONCENTRICITY AND/OR SEAT WIDTH CANNOT BE MAINTAINED, REPLACE AND
                            REGRIND THE VALVE SEATS.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Valve Seat Replacement</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">USE THE WINONA VAN NORMAN UNIVERSAL VALVE SEAT PULLER</emph>
                    to remove defective valve seat inserts as follows:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Choose the appropriate size pin collet and position the collet at the valve seat
                        insert.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Expand the pin collet by turning the small nut at the top of the bridge assembly.
                        Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150452">4.52</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Turn the large nut on the bridge assembly to pull the valve seat insert from the
                        cylinder head. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150453">4.53</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Unlock the pin collet by turning the small nut and discard the valve seat insert.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Select the appropriate size valve seat insert. Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="t4150409">"VALVE SEAT INSERT CHART".</hotlnk>
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>STANDARD SERVICE VALVE SEAT INSERTS ARE 0.002 IN. OVERSIZE. IF THE SEAT IS DAMAGED BEYOND
                            THE STANDARD DIAMETER, IT WILL BE NECESSARY TO MACHINE THE INSERT COUNTERBORE IN THE
                            CYLINDER HEAD FOR AN OVERSIZE SEAT INSERT. STANDARD SIZE INSERTS DO NOT REQUIRE COUNTERBORE
                            ENLARGEMENT.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4150452" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12051" filename="../figcg1/CG12051.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.52. Install Winona Van Norman Universal Valve Seat Puller.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150453" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12052" filename="../figcg1/CG12052.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.53. Pull Valve Seat Insert from Cylinder Head.</caption>
                </figure>
                <table id="t4150409">
                    <title>VALVE SEAT INSERT CHART</title>
                    <tgroup cols="3">
                        <colspec colname="1" colwidth="156p"/>
                        <colspec colname="2" colwidth="156p"/>
                        <colspec colname="3" colwidth="156p"/>
                        <spanspec namest="1" nameend="3" spanname="s1t3"/>
                        <spanspec namest="2" nameend="3" spanname="s2t3"/>
                        <thead>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>OVERSIZE</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colspan="2" spanname="s2t3">
                                    <para>DIAMETER OF CYLINDER HEAD COUNTERBORE</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>INSERT</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>INTAKE</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="3">
                                    <para>EXHAUST</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>002 in.* (STANDARD)</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>2.001 - 2.002 in.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="3">
                                    <para>1.626 - 1.627 in.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colname="1">
                                    <para>015 in.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="2">
                                    <para>2.011 - 2.012 in.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry colname="3">
                                    <para>1.639 - 1.640 in.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="3" spanname="s1t3">
                                    <para>* STANDARD SIZE SERVICE INSERT DOES NOT REQUIRE INSERT COUNTERBORE ENLARGEMENT
                                        BEFORE INSTALLING.
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the valve seat insert as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Chill the valve seat insert in a freezer for 30 minutes before installing.</para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Chilling the valve seat insert prevents peeling of metal from the cylinder head
                                counterbore during installation.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Align the insert to avoid cocking.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Drive the insert into its counterbore using
                        <emph type="bold">SE-4165</emph>
                        for the exhaust valve seat insert and
                        <emph type="bold">SE-4164</emph>
                        for the intake valve seat insert. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk document="e415_58.xml" xrefid="ef4150454">4.54</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Grind the new valve seat(s) to the specified angles and width. Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="hl4150405">"VALVE SEAT GRINDING"</hotlnk>
                    in this section.
                </para>
            </step1>
